  "text": "In apache/kafka, there are no actual Java annotations named @ConfigKey or @ConfigDef. Instead, the configuration documentation system is built around the `ConfigDef` class and its inner class `ConfigKey` (not annotations). The core definition is in `ConfigDef.java` which defines both the configuration schema class and the `ConfigKey` inner class (line 1237), along with documentation generation methods: `toHtml()`, `toHtmlTable()`, `toRst()`, and `toEnrichedRst()`. `AbstractConfig.java` is the base class that uses `ConfigDef.ConfigKey` for config access and documentation. Dedicated doc generators include `TransformationDoc.java` and `PredicateDoc.java` in the connect tools package. Numerous AbstractConfig subclasses define configs via `ConfigDef` and generate HTML documentation through `main` methods that call `CONFIG.toHtml()`, including `ProducerConfig`, `ConsumerConfig`, `AdminClientConfig`, `StreamsConfig`, `AbstractKafkaConfig`, `LogConfig`, `GroupConfig`, and various Connect/Mirror configs. `ConfigUtils.java`, `KafkaConfigSchema.java`, and `AbstractHerder.java` also use `ConfigDef.ConfigKey` directly for config metadata operations.",
